    "For part 1, it is straightforward to check that ζ A is a complete Boolean algebra isomorphism, so we only show that it respects the operators.",
    "Let A = ⟨A, ∧, -, ⊤, {■ i } i∈I ⟩.",
    "For x ∈ A, ζ A (■ A i x) = {y ∈ A \\ {⊥} | y ≤ ■ A i x} by the definition of ζ A, and ■ (Ap) b i ζ A (x) = {y ∈ A \\ {⊥} | R Ap i (y) ⊆ ζ A (x)∈ A \\ {⊥}, y ≤ ■ A i x iff R Ap i (y) ⊆ ζ A (x).",
    "Suppose y ≤ ■ A i x and consider a z such that yR Ap i z, which means that for all z ′ such that ⊥ ̸ = z ′ ≤ z, y ∧ ♦ A i z ′ ̸ = ⊥.",
    "It follows that z ≤ x, for if z ̸ ≤ x, then z ∧ -x ̸ = ⊥, so by the previous step, y ∧ ♦ A i (z ∧ -x) ̸ = ⊥, which implies y ∧ ♦ A i -x ̸ = ⊥, which contradicts y ≤ ■ A i x."
